Reviewing some basics of R

Which are the dimensions of the dataset?

You can use dim, nrow and ncol to get some information about the data you have in terms of its dimension. You can also get this information at the Environment panel, from the specific dataframe name dat. Also, when you are using RMarkdown you can see this when doing head(dat) or simply dat at the bottom left of the output table (see above). View(dat) will open a spreadsheet-style data viewer.

dim(dat) # Dimensions: rows and columns
nrow(dat) # Number of rows
ncol(dat) # Number of columns

Now, if we want to look for the number of genes with zero expression in the Liver, we could do the following:

counter <- 0 # Set counter to 0
for (i in 1:nrow(dat)) { # For each of the genes in the dataset
  if (dat$Liver[i] == 0) # If their expression is 0
    counter <- counter + 1 # Add +1 to the counter
}

#There are several ways to print the output:
print(paste("There are", counter, "number of genes with an expression equal to zero."))
print(paste("There are", counter, "number of genes with an expression equal to zero.", sep = "~"))
print(paste0("There are", counter, "number of genes with an expression equal to zero."))

This can be done using dplyr, a package for working with data frame like objects in a fast and memory-efficient way.

### Dplyr alternative
dat %>% 
  select(Liver) %>%
  filter(Liver == 0) %>%
  count()


# One-liner
x <- length(dat$Liver[which(dat$Liver==0)])
x

Apply family

For loops are easy-to-understand and code so one might be tented to used them too much. As opposed to other programming languages, R is not particularly good at running loops an so they might be good for low-intensity iterations, but they are not generally recommended with high-dimensional data. There are some other functions that are specifically designed to substitute loops in R. One of these sets of functions fall within the apply family.

This is how they can be used:

apply(X = dat[3:ncol(dat)],MARGIN = 2, FUN = mean) # Mean tissue expression 
lapply(3:ncol(dat), function(x) mean(dat[,x])) # Lapply() always returns a list
sapply(3:ncol(dat), function(x) mean(dat[,x])) # Sapply() returns a vector

dplyr & tidyr

Reshaping a dataframe with pivot_longer() and/or pivot_wider(). Here we will use pivot_longer() to put all the expression values into 1 column, grouping all the tissues into another.

dat %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 3:ncol(dat), names_to = "Tissue", values_to = "Expression")

Once we have reshaped the dataframe, we can filter with filter() to select a specific tissue and get the mean expression.

dat %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 3:ncol(dat), names_to = "Tissue", values_to = "Expression") %>%
  filter(Tissue == "Lung") %>%
  summarise(mean(Expression))

OrganTissue <- dat %>%
  head() %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 3:ncol(dat), names_to = "Tissue", values_to = "Expression") %>%
  separate(col = Tissue, into = c("Organ", "Tissue2"), sep = "_",
           remove = TRUE,  #remove `Tissue` column
           extra = "merge", #To only split a specified number of times `extra = merge`
           fill = "left")  %>% #To fill with NAs the
  mutate(Organ = coalesce(Organ, Tissue2) # Fill NAs from Organ column with values from Tissue2 column
         )

And now we will plot the counts of tissues by organ. We will use this to show some examples on how to tune a plot.

OrganTissue %>%
  group_by(Organ) %>%
  summarise(CountTissues = n_distinct(Tissue2)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Organ, CountTissues), y = CountTissues, fill = Organ)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() + #we flip the plot so the original X axis labels are easy to read and we do not have to rotate our heads
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0.005, 0), limits = c(0,15)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = CountTissues, hjust = -1, color = Organ), size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Number of tissues by organ", subtitle = "GTEX data", caption = "IBECourse Practicum") + # Add title, subtitle and caption
  ylab("") + xlab("") + #Remove x and y axis labels (possible to do when there is an explanatory plot title)
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "none", #Remove legen since there are already the labels on the axis to identify each organ
        plot.title.position = "plot", #Align the title and subtitle to the plot, not the vertical axis
        axis.line = element_blank(), #remove axis lines
        axis.ticks = element_blank(), #remove axis ticks
        axis.text.x = element_blank(), #remove X axis labels
        axis.text.y = element_text(color = "grey50")
        )

Functions

You can write your own functions in order to make repetitive operations using a single command. Actually, this is good practice for making reproducible results.

For example, if we want to obtain the maximum expression of a gene we could write a function like this:

max_gene_expression <- function(gene_name) {
  coord_gene <- which(dat$Description == gene_name)
  
  return(print(paste0("Max ", gene_name, " expression: ", max(dat[coord_gene,3:ncol(dat)]), " TPM.")))
}

The max_gene_expression() function has been defined and now it can run with any gene wed like to add:

max_gene_expression(gene_name = "BRCA1")
[1] "Max BRCA1 expression: 19.7684 TPM."
max_gene_expression(gene_name = "CTCF")
[1] "Max CTCF expression: 53.0068 TPM."
